11. Retentlon of tha quantity of final vowels originally long. This is much less common in Terence than in Plautus. Many instances given by Wagner are not certain. Probably this retention takes place only when it is helped by a pause, eg. 437 potin es mi verum dicere'.

Elatus is admitted :

(1) When there isa change of speaker, e. g. 616, 665.

(a) When a line is broken by a strong pause, eg. 345.

(3) When a word is isolated by the sense, eg. 264 incertum. (4) Alter the fourth foot of an Iambic or Trochaic Tetrameter.

It is hardly necessary to note that the interjection 0 is not

elided before vowels, e. g. 769, 817 ; nor is em, cs. 604. Occasionally a long vowel is shortened instead ol being elided,
